    <h2 slot="heading">Cleaning up afterwards</h2>
    <p>The scale of the clean-up job depends on how much water has leaked. If your home is flooded and your furniture or belongings are wet through, you'll probably need to wait for your insurer to send their loss adjuster to you.</p>

    <p>They'll then take care of drying out and repairing your home and contents. In the meantime, move everything out of harm's way to prevent further damage.</p>

    <p>If the leak isn't too bad, you can try to clean up yourself. Just make sure you don't throw away any damaged items before documenting them if you intend to make a claim. Proof of purchase, pictures and any serial numbers will help when it comes to making a claim.</p>

    <p>Remember, home insurance policies differ so it's best to speak to your insurance company if you have any worries about burst pipe claims.</p>

